    <patterns>
      <pattern name="Error code → user message map (binding)" location="projects/spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r5/notes/insights-engine-assistant-integration-brief.md §5.1">
        The integration brief §5.1 column 4 IS the source of truth for per-code
        user messages. Encode the 12-code matrix as a TypeScript const map
        (e.g., `ERROR_CODE_MESSAGES: Record&lt;string, string&gt;`) co-located
        with the renderer. The map keys are the stable `errorCode` extensions
        (e.g., `query.required`, `ai.intent-classification.disabled`) plus
        synthetic keys for 401 (`auth.401`) and 429 (`rate-limit.429`) since
        those don't carry an `errorCode` in the contract.
      </pattern>
      <pattern name="ProblemDetails TypeScript type (forward-compat)" location="(R5-local — define in renderer's types.ts)">
        Define TypeScript shape with required fields + `[key: string]: unknown`
        index signature so v1.1 extensions pass through unchanged.

        ```typescript
        export type InsightsProblemDetails = {
          type?: string;
          title?: string;
          status?: number;
          detail?: string;
          errorCode?: string;
          correlationId?: string;
          [key: string]: unknown;
        };
        ```
      </pattern>
      <pattern name="Retry policy state machine (binding for FR-16 special cases)" location="(R5-local — embed in renderer or extract to insights-error-handler.ts)">
        Encode as an explicit state machine:

        ```typescript
        type RetryDecision =
          | { kind: 'no-retry' }
          | { kind: 'retry-with-force-mode'; forceMode: 'playbook' | 'rag' }
          | { kind: 'retry-after-backoff'; backoffMs: number };

        function decideRetry(
          response: { status: number; errorCode?: string },
          originalRequest: { forceMode?: string; intentSignal?: 'playbook' | 'rag' },
          attemptNumber: number  // 1 = original; 2 = first retry
        ): RetryDecision { ... }
        ```

        Rules (binding):
        - 503 `ai.intent-classification.disabled` + no `forceMode` on original +
          `intentSignal` available → `retry-with-force-mode`.
        - 500 `INSIGHTS_ASSISTANT_INTERNAL_ERROR` + attemptNumber === 1 →
          `retry-after-backoff` with 1000ms.
        - All other codes + any attemptNumber &gt;= 2 → `no-retry`.

        Test exhaustively — this is the FR-16 binding contract.
      </pattern>
      <pattern name="`Retry-After` header parsing (ADR-016)" location="(R5-local utility)">
        Per ADR-016 + RFC 7231: `Retry-After` MAY be either an integer
        (delta-seconds) or an HTTP-date. Parse both; show as countdown in UX.
        Renderer does NOT auto-retry on 429 — user clicks manually.
      </pattern>
      <pattern name="No-leakage assertion (ADR-018)" location="(unit test discipline)">
        Author a test that injects a fabricated error response with `detail`
        containing strings that simulate document content (e.g., "DRAFT —
        Acme APA: This agreement is between..."), prompt text (e.g.,
        "You are a helpful assistant..."), and a fake stack trace
        ("at System.Threading...."). Assert that the rendered DOM contains
        NONE of these strings. Assert the rendered DOM DOES contain the
        column-4 user-facing message for the code.
      </pattern>
      <pattern name="Correlation-id surfacing (FR-17 / SC-16)" location="(R5-local rendering convention)">
        Render correlationId as small mono-font text below the user message,
        e.g., `&lt;Text size={100} font="monospace"&gt;{correlationId}&lt;/Text&gt;`.
        Provide a copy-to-clipboard affordance (Fluent v9 `Button appearance="subtle"`
        with `Copy24Regular` icon). Use the existing Fluent v9 / Spaarke
        copy-to-clipboard helper from `Spaarke.UI.Components` if one exists;
        otherwise inline `navigator.clipboard.writeText`. Visual hierarchy:
        user message PRIMARY, correlationId SECONDARY.
      </pattern>
      <pattern name="ADR-028 reauth flow on 401" location="src/client/shared/Spaarke.Auth/">
        On 401 with no `errorCode`, call the existing `@spaarke/auth`
        `useAuth()` `refreshToken()` / equivalent helper. If success → single
        retry. If failure (refresh token expired / revoked) → surface "Your
        session expired" + "Sign in again" affordance. MUST use existing
        helper; NO parallel auth logic.
      </pattern>
    </patterns>
  </knowledge>

  <context>
    <background>
      R5 ships the `insights.query` tool integration through the SpaarkeAi
      three-pane shell. The two-path response renderer (`InsightsResponseRenderer`,
      shipped by task 026) handles success responses (playbook structured
      envelope + RAG citation-grounded prose). This task completes the picture
      by wiring contract-binding error handling for all 12 error codes from
      integration brief §5.1.

      The 12-code matrix is the FR-16 binding contract. Each code has a stable
      `errorCode` extension (per ADR-019 ProblemDetails) and a per-code
      user-facing message in integration brief §5.1 column 4. R5 MUST encode
      this mapping explicitly — the LLM cannot improvise an error message
      from `detail` text because `detail` MAY contain operator-relevant
      diagnostics that are NOT user-facing per ADR-018 (no information leakage).

      Two retry policies are special-cased per plan.md D2-19 + spec FR-16:
      - 503 `ai.intent-classification.disabled` is a kill-switch surfaced by
        the BFF when the intent classifier is operationally disabled. If R5
        already knows the intent (slash command path with explicit mode), it
        can bypass the classifier by retrying with `forceMode` set. This is
        a real value-recovery: instead of surfacing "temporarily disabled" to
        a user who just typed `/ask-insights rag ...`, R5 retries the same
        request with `forceMode: "rag"` and gets a real answer.
      - 500 `INSIGHTS_ASSISTANT_INTERNAL_ERROR` is the generic internal-error
        catch-all. Per integration brief column 4: "Retry ONCE with 1s
        backoff. On second 500: surface error + log." This handles transient
        BFF failures (e.g., brief Service Bus blip) without forcing user
        retry; the 1s backoff prevents thundering-herd on a genuinely
        struggling BFF.

      All other codes are non-retryable. Auto-retrying a 400 would just fail
      again with the same code. Auto-retrying a 429 violates ADR-016 (honor
      `Retry-After`; let the user click retry manually after the timer).
      Auto-retrying a kill-switch-induced 503 (e.g., `ai.insights.disabled`)
      doesn't change anything — the kill switch is still off.

      `correlationId` propagation is the operator-facing diagnostic surface.
      The chain: task 024 generates the ID per Assistant turn → task 025
      HTTP client propagates it as `x-correlation-id` request header → BFF
      includes it as the `correlationId` ProblemDetails extension on errors
      (plus the `X-Insights-*` response headers on success) → this task
      surfaces it in the error UI. End-to-end App Insights / Kusto
      correlation works because every link in the chain uses the same ID.

      Information-leakage discipline (ADR-018 + integration brief §5.2) is
      load-bearing. The error UI MUST NOT show: document content (PII / IP
      risk), prompt text (system-prompt exposure), LLM raw output (could
      contain hallucinated content presented as authoritative), or stack
      traces (architecture disclosure). The server contract enforces this on
      the wire; this task enforces it client-side by rendering ONLY the
      column-4 message + correlationId. Any server-supplied `detail` field
      is Console-logged for diagnostics but never rendered.

      This task is the third + final task of the P2-G6/G7 Insights tool
      integration suite that consumes the binding contract. After this task
      completes, task 030 runs end-to-end smoke tests on Spaarke Dev (Wave D7
      synthetic GUIDs + SME walkthrough). After task 030 + task 031 (Phase 2
      integration verification) complete, Phase 2 closes.
    </background>
